              "children": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "TbmKj",
                  "name": "headline",
                  "fill": "#F8FAFC",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "Reading intent changes how people hold information",
                  "lineHeight": 1.1,
                  "fontFamily": "Geist",
                  "fontSize": 28,
                  "fontWeight": "700"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "W2kEp",
                  "name": "copy",
                  "fill": "#D6E0EA",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "Strong learning products shape reading intent before they dump information. When the reader knows what to notice, the content becomes easier to hold and easier to reuse later.\n\nThat matters even more in card-based learning. If every lesson is forced into the same fixed height, longer lessons either get cramped or fragmented. A better pattern is simple: let the article breathe, keep progress visible, and keep the next action obvious.\n\nThis is the core rule for the Krux reader: the interface should stay out of the way while the lesson does the work.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.7,
                  "fontFamily": "Source Serif 4",
                  "fontSize": 17,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "group",
                  "id": "GuJHW",
                  "children": [
